06608nam a22009855i 9780823280292DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232802927 a10.1515/97808232802922doi  a(DE-B1597)554967  a(OCoLC)1038054246  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0430002bisacsh04a155.9/322300aTrauma and Transcendence :bSuffering and the Limits of Theory /ced. by Eric Boynton, Peter Capretto. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tintroduction. The Limits of Theory in Trauma and Transcendence -- tpart I. Constructive Phenomenologies of Trauma -- tchapter 1. Two Trauma Communities: A Philosophical Archaeology of Cultural and Clinical Trauma Theories -- tchapter 2. Phenomenological-Contextualism All the Way Down: An Existential and Ethical Perspective on Emotional Trauma -- tchapter 3. Traumatized by Transcendence: My Other's Keeper -- tchapter 4. Evil, Trauma, and the Building of Absences -- tchapter 5. The Unsettling of Perception: Levinas and the Anarchic Trauma -- tpart II. Social and Political Analyses of Traumatic Experience -- tchapter 6. The Artful Politics of Trauma: Rancière's Critique of Lyotard -- tchapter 7. Black Embodied Wounds and the Traumatic Impact of the White Imaginary -- tchapter 8. Perpetrator Trauma and Collective Guilt: My Lai -- tchapter 9. The Psychic Economy and Fetishization of Traumatic Lived Experience -- tpart III. Theological Aporia in the Aftermath of Trauma -- tchapter 10. Theopoetics of Trauma -- tchapter 11. Body-Wise: Re-Fleshing Christian Spiritual Practice in Trauma's Wake -- tchapter 12. Trauma and Theology: Prospects and Limits in Light of the Cross -- tafterword. The Transcendence of Trauma: Prospects for the Continental Philosophy of Religion -- tacknowledgments -- tbibliography -- tcontributors -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTrauma theory has become a burgeoning site of research in recent decades, often demanding interdisciplinary reflections on trauma as a phenomenon that defies disciplinary ownership. While this research has always been challenged by the temporal, affective, and corporeal dimensions of trauma itself, trauma theory now faces theoretical and methodological obstacles given its growing interdisciplinarity. Trauma and Transcendence gathers scholars in philosophy, theology, psychoanalysis, and social theory to engage the limits and prospects of trauma's transcendence. This volume draws attention to the increasing challenge of deciding whether trauma's unassimilable quality can be wielded as a defense of traumatic experience against reductionism, or whether it succumbs to a form of obscurantism.Contributors: Eric Boynton, Peter Capretto, Tina Chanter, Vincenzo Di Nicola, Ronald Eyerman, Donna Orange, Shelly Rambo, Mary-Jane Rubenstein, Hilary Jerome Scarsella, Eric Severson, Marcia Mount Shoop, Robert D. Stolorow, George Yancy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAporia. 0aPsychic trauma. 0aStress (Psychology). 0aSufferingxPhilosophy. 0aSufferingxReligious aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Post-Structuralism.2bisacsh  aContinental Philosophy.  aEthics.  aPhenomenology.  aPhilosophy of Religion.  aPhilosophy.  aPsychoanalysis.  aSociology.  aTheology.  aTheory.  aTrauma.1 aBoynton, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapretto, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapretto, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.